1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,000
 (Applause)

2
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:09,000
 "Swing Low," written by Wallace Willis in the late 1800s,

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000
 made more popular in the 1900s by a group of African-American singers

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
 called the Fisk Jubilee Singers.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:20,000
 This song has been around for a while in its transcended genre.

6
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:25,000
 It's been sung by Dolly Parton, it's been sung by Johnny Cash,

7
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:27,000
 it's been sung by the Beatles,

8
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:32,000
 it's been sung by Johnny Cash, it's been sung by Alicia Keys.

9
00:00:32,000 --> 00:00:36,000
 And the reason people sing this song is because of the themes in the song.

10
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:38,000
 The song is a bit of a retelling,

11
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:41,000
 emphasizing on certain parts of the story of Elijah.

12
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:45,000
 Now, Elijah is my personal favorite Bible character.

13
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:49,000
 I've named my son Elias after him.

14
00:00:49,000 --> 00:00:55,000
 The story of Elijah is of a prophet who is taken from Earth.

15
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:01,000
 And the chariot swings low and carries him to Heaven.

16
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,000
 Themes of hope.

17
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:06,000
 That's why this song was sung.

18
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:10,000
 But see, the singers of this song, African-American slaves,

19
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:12,000
 actually sung it for multiple reasons.

20
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:15,000
 One of the other reasons was that it was a bit of a code,

21
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:16,000
 it was hidden language.

22
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:20,000
 See, the idea of "Swinging Low" was a reference to the fact that Harriet Tubman,

23
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
 a woman who was known for helping slaves escape the South

24
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:29,000
 via the Underground Railroad, would be close.

25
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:32,000
 And so African-American slaves would sing this

26
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
 as a way of communicating to one another

27
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 without letting their oppressors know

28
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:45,000
 that there was a chance that they could escape to rest that very night.

29
00:01:45,000 --> 00:01:53,000
 "Swing low, sweet chariot, coming for to carry me home."

30
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:56,000
 You can see that this song is pretty weighty.

31
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:01,000
 It's pretty powerful lyrics, both to the singer and to those listening.

32
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
 A song speaking of hope, of a future peace, of a future rest for people.

33
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 "Coming for to carry me home."

34
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:13,000
 In these lyrics, home is not just the place you go to rest, to sleep,

35
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:15,000
 to lay your head down.

36
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,000
 No, home is a place that is providing you freedom from conflict,

37
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:24,000
 freedom from oppression, freedom from death and pain.

38
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:27,000
 It's a place of actual rest.

39
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 See, this is a song that was sung by people done wrong, but unbroken,

40
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:39,000
 by the land they lived in, weary from the oppression of their circumstances,

41
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 but still pointing their hope towards a future rest from their oppressors,

42
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 towards a future restoration of their dignity.

43
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,000
 This was a song of rest for the restless,

44
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:02,000
 a song for all of those who were truly weary.

45
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:06,000
 The second song we look at over this Advent series

46
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:10,000
 comes from a guy who sings it, but ironically enough,

47
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
 a few seconds before, it had been mute for a long time.

48
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 He's a well-educated man.

49
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
 He's grown up knowing the Scriptures extensively.

50
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:23,000
 An older man who's been serving God his whole life,

51
00:03:23,000 --> 00:03:27,000
 which would mean that he would have witnessed the deterioration of his homeland

52
00:03:27,000 --> 00:03:31,000
 while waiting for God to fulfill a promise.

53
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:33,000
 He's a man of God from the tribe of Levi.

54
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:39,000
 He's a priest wrestling with the tensions of seeing his people suffer for so long.

55
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
 He would have known the promises that one day a Messiah would come and rescue them,

56
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:46,000
 but he hadn't seen it yet.

57
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:49,000
 This man was Zechariah, the priest.

58
00:03:49,000 --> 00:03:53,000
 See, Zechariah wasn't a marginalized individual.

59
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:57,000
 He wasn't on the outskirts of society.

60
00:03:57,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 He would have been someone that would have been seen as a bit more of a prestigious fellow,

61
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:05,000
 had a sense of honor,

62
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:10,000
 but yet he too felt the same oppression that people like Mary

63
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:17,000
 that we talked about last week would have been feeling and singing about.

64
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:25,000
 The first story we get of Zechariah is of him doubting the Word of God,

65
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,000
 which is odd because I guess when I think about it,

66
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,000
 Zechariah is a priest.

67
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,000
 I was thinking of this yesterday.

68
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,000
 I'm like, "Man, if I were a priest and I'd been serving God for a long time,

69
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,000
 and it's like, 'Oh, your name gets to be in the Bible,

70
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:36,000
 and the story's going to be written about you,'

71
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 I would hope it would be about something other than my doubt."

72
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:42,000
 But this is Zechariah's case.

73
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:45,000
 See, Zechariah is in a bit of a predicament.

74
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:50,000
 He's an older guy, and he and his wife are without child.

75
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,000
 They've been wanting a child for a while.

76
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:56,000
 But there's been this prayer and these prayers and these prayers,

77
00:04:56,000 --> 00:04:57,000
 and God has done nothing.

78
00:04:57,000 --> 00:04:59,000
 He has failed to act.

79
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:04,000
 It's like God has been silent.

80
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:09,000
 So one day Zechariah goes to fulfill his priestly duties of lighting incense

81
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
 in the holiest place in the temple.

82
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:14,000
 And an angel appears to him and says, "Zechariah, good news.

83
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:17,000
 You and your wife are going to have a kid.

84
00:05:17,000 --> 00:05:19,000
 God has heard your prayers.

85
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 We should be rejoicing you."

86
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:24,000
 And Zechariah is any critical-thinking, rational individual.

87
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:28,000
 His first thought is, "I'm a bit old."

88
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 You know, like, you know, if you're later down the road,

89
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:33,000
 that's probably not what you're thinking is about having a kid

90
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,000
 when you're in your 70s, 80s, or 90s.

91
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
 That's the space that Zechariah is in.

92
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
 And an angel says, "You're going to have a kid."

93
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:43,000
 He's first thinking, "Yeah, that's probably not possible, mate."

94
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:46,000
 It puts him in this position of doubt

95
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:49,000
 because he's been praying for so long,

96
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:51,000
 waiting for God to answer this prayer, and it hasn't happened.

97
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:53,000
 He's probably reflecting, thinking, "Man, God,

98
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
 if you really wanted to step in and do a miracle,

99
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
 why didn't you hit me up in my 30s and 40s?"

100
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:04,000
 That would have been the perfect time for you to show up and do a miracle.

101
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
 So this is a prayer that's been unanswered,

102
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:09,000
 much like the bigger prayer that him and his people

103
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:13,000
 have been praying for salvation

104
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 while they remain under a deeply oppressive system.

105
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:21,000
 See, Zechariah's faith was weary. He was tired.

106
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:24,000
 And that happens to us sometimes, too.

107
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:27,000
 We, too, get tired. We, too, get weary.

108
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
 Sometimes faith is a thing of endurance,

109
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:34,000
 and our circumstances can impact our stamina.

110
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 This was the case for Zechariah,

111
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:40,000
 and neither him nor his father or his father's father's generations before

112
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 had been waiting for a while for this promise to be fulfilled,

113
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
 for God to act on their behalf,

114
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
 when nothing had happened yet.

115
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:50,000
 And so in his little altercation with the angel--

116
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:53,000
 the angel makes a bit of an example out of him--

117
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
 the angel takes away his ability to speak for the next nine months,

118
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 and Zechariah would sit and would have to think and process for a bit.

119
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:05,000
 And, you know, what the angel says comes true.

120
00:07:05,000 --> 00:07:07,000
 His wife Elizabeth is pregnant, has a child,

121
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:09,000
 and they're all wondering, "What are you going to name the baby?

122
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:10,000
 What are you going to name the baby?"

123
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:12,000
 And Elizabeth is like, "Oh, we'll name him John."

124
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:14,000
 And they look at Zechariah, thinking, "That surely can't be the name.

125
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:15,000
 Why John?"

126
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:17,000
 And so they look at Zechariah, and they're like, "What are we going to name him?"

127
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
 And he writes it down.

128
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:23,000
 And to their surprise, when he holds up the sheet of paper, it says "John."

129
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:26,000
 And immediately his voice comes back.

130
00:07:26,000 --> 00:07:30,000
 And the first thing he does, a bit different than when he was doubting--

131
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:33,000
 the last time he spoke, he was doubting the angel's word.

132
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:40,000
 This time, as his voice comes back, we look at Luke 1, 67, and he says this.

133
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
 "His father Zechariah was filled with the Holy Spirit

134
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:47,000
 and prophesied, 'Praise be to the Lord, the God of Israel,

135
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
 because he has come to his people and redeemed them.

136
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:55,000
 He has raised up a horn of salvation in the house of his servant David,

137
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:59,000
 as he said he would through the prophets of long ago.

138
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 Salvation from our enemies and from the hands of all those who hate us,

139
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:08,000
 to show mercy to our ancestors and to remember his holy covenant,

140
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:13,000
 the oath he swore to our father Abraham, to rescue us from the hands of our enemies

141
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:19,000
 and to enable us to serve him without fear and holiness and righteousness

142
00:08:19,000 --> 00:08:23,000
 before him all of our days.'"

143
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:29,000
 See, this is the first thing that comes out of Zechariah after nine months of stewing.

144
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:33,000
 Within this song, I believe there's some pretty compelling truths

145
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:36,000
 that show us a couple of things about rest,

146
00:08:36,000 --> 00:08:41,000
 about how we can be at rest in this current moment,

147
00:08:41,000 --> 00:08:44,000
 regardless of what's going on, and how we can find rest,

148
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:48,000
 where to look, where to turn our eyes if we are in need of rest.

149
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:51,000
 And I would think this is pretty relevant to a lot of us.

150
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
 The past couple of years in Hong Kong hasn't been the most restful.

151
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:58,000
 When you do your reflection back on the year in a couple of weeks

152
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:01,000
 around New Year's Eve and you're celebrating,

153
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 if someone asks you how their year's going,

154
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:11,000
 your guess is that I doubt you'll say it's just been a real restful year.

155
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:15,000
 And so this passage has something to show each of us about what rest looks like,

156
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:18,000
 because we long for rest.

157
00:09:18,000 --> 00:09:24,000
 We were made to live within that shalom and that wholeness that God offers us.

158
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:28,000
 And Zechariah, after not speaking for months, still in this system,

159
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:31,000
 nothing has changed about the big picture.

160
00:09:31,000 --> 00:09:33,000
 Let's get that straight.

161
00:09:33,000 --> 00:09:36,000
 It's not like nine months later, all of a sudden, all the oppression is just gone.

162
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,000
 No, nine months later, his baby has come,

163
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:41,000
 and the Holy Spirit comes upon him, fills him,

164
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:44,000
 and he sings that God has come.

165
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,000
 He sings that there is rest.

166
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:52,000
 And I think as we look into this, we can find for ourselves what rest looks like

167
00:09:52,000 --> 00:09:55,000
 and how we can enter into it.

168
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,000
 So Zechariah's song opens with praises.

169
00:09:58,000 --> 00:10:00,000
 He praises God because he has come.

170
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:03,000
 And that's what this whole season's all about, right?

171
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:05,000
 Like God has come to his people.

172
00:10:05,000 --> 00:10:09,000
 That's the whole idea of Advent, the waiting for God to come.

173
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:13,000
 And Zechariah opens his mouth and says, "God has come."

174
00:10:13,000 --> 00:10:16,000
 It's been just nine months ago.

175
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:19,000
 Zechariah was doubting that God would do the very thing he promised to do,

176
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:24,000
 and that was a bit of a smaller thing compared to the bigger scale picture.

177
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:27,000
 He was doubting the words of the angel, but now Zechariah is saying,

178
00:10:27,000 --> 00:10:31,000
 "God has come. God is here. Hallelujah, he's here."

179
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:34,000
 Like this has been 1,600 years of prophecy unfulfilled,

180
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:38,000
 of people desperately longing for some type of salvation,

181
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:41,000
 for God to come and to save them from their oppression,

182
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:44,000
 and Zechariah is saying, "God is here."

183
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:46,000
 We look at the verse again, and he said,

184
00:10:46,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 "Through his prophets, holy prophets of long ago,

185
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:53,000
 salvation from our enemies and from the hand of all those who hate us,

186
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:58,000
 to show mercy to our ancestors and to remember his holy covenant,

187
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,000
 the oath he swore to our father Abraham."

188
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:07,000
 See, this was a bit of an old, old promise, an old covenant made a long time ago.

189
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:12,000
 Many have come, many have passed, and it's not happened yet.

190
00:11:12,000 --> 00:11:16,000
 And we've all been in that position as well, where something was promised a while ago,

191
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:19,000
 and we've been waiting, and we've been waiting, and we find ourselves,

192
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:22,000
 it's been so long that we doubt that the promise was even made, more or less,

193
00:11:22,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 that it would ever come through.

194
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:31,000
 This would be the state of the audience that Zechariah would be singing and prophesying to.

195
00:11:31,000 --> 00:11:34,000
 The Jewish people, that's where they would be.

196
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,000
 So, in Zechariah's first line, that God has come,

197
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:42,000
 he's actually offering them his first way of finding rest.

198
00:11:42,000 --> 00:11:44,000
 And what is that rest, you might ask?

199
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:52,000
 It's this, we can rest assured that God has remembered his promise.

200
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:54,000
 I mean, we're just saying that, right?

201
00:11:54,000 --> 00:11:56,000
 The promise still stands.

202
00:11:56,000 --> 00:12:01,000
 No mountain, no walls, like, the promise still stands.

203
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:05,000
 Advent is our reminder of a God who has heard his people,

204
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:11,000
 who has been faithful to his word, who doesn't say one thing and does another.

205
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:13,000
 But a God who remembers his promise.

206
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:15,000
 He hadn't forgotten about his people.

207
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 And this is funny, this is like the second time this has happened.

208
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:20,000
 See, if we look back in scripture, we look at the Exodus story,

209
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:26,000
 these people are under oppression for 400 years underneath a deeply oppressive system,

210
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:29,000
 similar to the way that they are in the first century.

211
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:33,000
 And they think God hasn't heard them, but he breaks into their silence,

212
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:36,000
 and he sends them Moses to rescue them.

213
00:12:36,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 But this time it'd be a little different.

214
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:40,000
 God's not sending Moses.

215
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 He's not sending an Elijah.

216
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:48,000
 No, God himself is coming into the brokenness, into the systems of oppression,

217
00:12:48,000 --> 00:12:52,000
 into our darkness, to be with us.

218
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:57,000
 And today we can rest assured because our God keeps his promise.

219
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:01,000
 His promise still stands.

220
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:03,000
 His words are still true today.

221
00:13:03,000 --> 00:13:07,000
 We think about how, for a lot of us, a promise can feel conditional.

222
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
 When we make a promise to someone or we say we'll do something,

223
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:16,000
 it's depending on, well, in the next eight years or over this period of time.

224
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:20,000
 This promise was made 1,600 years previous.

225
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:23,000
 The state of the people of Israel had changed.

226
00:13:23,000 --> 00:13:28,000
 They had gone from being a nation that was following God, and God kept his promise,

227
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:32,000
 to being a nation that fell into idolatry, but yet God still keeps his promise.

228
00:13:32,000 --> 00:13:35,000
 A nation that was given God's presence in the Ark of the Covenant

229
00:13:35,000 --> 00:13:40,000
 and lost it in their unfaithfulness, but God chooses to still keep his promise.

230
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:44,000
 A nation that had been unfaithful, following after God,

231
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:50,000
 placing their faith in other things, in themselves, and God chooses to be faithful.

232
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:53,000
 A nation under foreign occupation and the people are losing hope

233
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:56,000
 about whether God hears them, doubting if he's even there,

234
00:13:56,000 --> 00:14:00,000
 just going through the rhythms and the routines without meaning any of it.

235
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:04,000
 And God keeps his promise.

236
00:14:04,000 --> 00:14:07,000
 There's something to hold onto here.

237
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:10,000
 God will keep his promise.

238
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:16,000
 He keeps his word, independent of how we failed, doubted, or forgotten him.

239
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:18,000
 That's just the God we serve.

240
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 He's consistent. He's not going to waver.

241
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:24,000
 If he says yes, it'll be yes.

